      "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
      "body": "This library does not expose any way to do this. You can obtain r and s by parsing the signature (easiest way is to call `secp256k1_signature_parse_der` and then `secp256k1_signature_serialize_compact` to get a compact encoding, then R is the first 32 bytes and s is the last 32 bytes).\r\n\r\n`v` is harder, you need to back-compute the signature to determine the full R point. This library does not even do this computation because it is unnecessary for signature verification. Probably your best bet is to use sage or something.",
