      "body": "This is very difficult since there are really 3 different signature encodings:\r\n\r\n1. Plain (r, s) where r and s are 32 byte big endian integers (64 total bytes)\r\n2. Recoverable (r, s, v) where r and s are 32 byte big endian integers, and v is a single byte used for recovery (65 total bytes)\r\n3. Bitcoin compact signatures which are a version/recovery value, r, and s.  This too is 65 bytes.\r\n\r\nBecause of this, you can't really disambiguate 2 and 3.  If you KNOW its in format 2 or format 3 you can do this yourself by getting the first or last byte of the compact representation.  The API for compact signatures currently assumes 1 outright.  Even if you know which format the internal representation of the sig is 64 bytes and would need to be modified (i've already corrected the documentation that one should expect it to be sizeof(secp256k1_ecdsa_signature) not 64 exactly)",
